The E field associated with a time-varying current is different from the E
field associated with electrostatics. An electrostatic field exerts an
attraction or repulsion between charges. But the force associated with a
time-varying current is a dragging force: it causes charges to move parallel
(or anti-parallel) to the current's direction.

This time-varying field has been named an Electrokinetic field or Ek. This
is the field that is responsible for induction.

Its intensity is proportional to the rate of change of current flow and
inversely proportional to r (distance) and to cSQR. It is equal to the
negative time derivative of A, the magnetic vector potential. or,
Ek= -dA/dt.

Integrate this and we get A = - integral(Ek) + a constant

The integral of Ek may be referred to as the electrokinetic impulse. so, we
may say that the magnetic vector potential created by a current at a point
in space is equal to the negative of the electrokinetic impulse produced by
this current at the time the current is switched on.

The electrokinetic impulse is a measurable quantity (in principle) so the
above represents both a definition and a physical interpretation of A.
Please see, Jefimenko' &quot;Causality, Electromagnetic Induction and
Gravitation&quot; Section 2-4. You *have* ordered it, haven't you, Benj?

It will be an interesting challenge to figure out how to measure it, but at
least, Mr. Entropy, you will know what you are looking for.

