It is only the Lorenz gauge that reflects the capacity of the
potentials to propagate across space at speed c, reflecting the fact
that EM interactions occur on the mutual light-cone of each of the
pair of interacting electrons.  This gauge reflects the continuity
condition (in 3D vector form) that c A = u V.  This ensures that both
the scalar potential (V) and the vector potential (A) 'stay in synch'
&amp; both propagate at c in any inertial frame moving at velocity u
relative to the (instantaneous) frame where both electrons were first
at rest before they started to interact.  At the end of the day, both
the potentials (&amp; their derivatives - the fields) cannot be measured:
only the relative motion of the electrons across space over time are
measurable - the rest is theory. It is also useful to think of the
potentials as Aristotle would have: as the capability (&amp; possibility)
to generate change in the world.
